<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910502-0196</DOCNO><DOCID>910502-0196.</DOCID><HL>   Bloomingdale's Will Close   Its Oldest Branch Store</HL><DATE>05/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CMAFC T.CMP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Bloomingdale's said it decided to close itsoldest branch store, in Fresh Meadows, N.Y., rather thanundertake extensive renovations required to keep itcompetitive.   The closing, which will occur in July, will reduce thenumber of stores in the retail chain to 15. The Fresh Meadowsbranch, which opened in 1949, accounted for 2% ofBloomingdale's 1990 sales of $1.2 billion. Bloomingdale'salso said the branch, which has 127 full-time employees and150 part-timers, is near another of the chain's stores andthe businesses of the two outlets overlapped significantly.</LP><TEXT>   Last year, Bloomingdale's closed branches in Dallas andStamford, Conn., and opened a branch in West Palm Beach, Fla.   Bloomingdale's is a unit of Federated Department StoresInc.</TEXT></DOC>